com.roscopeco.moxy.api

Interface MoxyMultiVerifier


  • public interface MoxyMultiVerifier

    Implementations of this interface allow multiple mocks invocations to be verified after use. They are returned by the MoxyEngine.assertMocks(com.roscopeco.moxy.api.InvocationRunnable) method. For example:

    
 assertMocks(() -> {
   mock1.method1(any());
   mock1.method2(anyInt(), eq("Hello"));

   mock2.method1(anyBoolean());
 }).wereAllCalled();

    Individual engines will usually provide their own implementation of this interface, as verifying will require internal knowledge of the engine's mocking strategy.

    Since:
    1.0
    Author:
    Ross Bamford <roscopeco AT gmail DOT com>

    • Method Detail

      • wereNotCalled

        void wereNotCalled()

        Verify that none of the mock methods were called at all.

        Throws AssertionFailedError if a single invocation was matched, or MultipleFailuresError if multiple calls were matched. In the latter case, the individual calls that matched will each have a nested AssertionFailedError.

        Since:
        1.0

      • wereAllCalled

        MoxyMultiVerifier wereAllCalled()

        Verify that all the mock methods were called at least once, with the arguments specified in the call.

        Note the subtle difference from wereAllCalledExactly(int), which expects an exact number of calls.

        Throws AssertionFailedError if a single invocation wasn't matched, or MultipleFailuresError if multiple calls weren't matched. In the latter case, the individual calls that didn't match will each have a nested AssertionFailedError.

        Returns:
        this.
        Since:
        1.0

      • wereAllCalledExactly

        MoxyMultiVerifier wereAllCalledExactly(int expectedTimes)

        Verify that all the mock methods were called exactly expectedTimes with the arguments specified in the call.

        Throws AssertionFailedError if a single invocation wasn't matched, or MultipleFailuresError if multiple calls weren't matched. In the latter case, the individual calls that didn't match will each have a nested AssertionFailedError.

        Parameters:
        expectedTimes - The expected number of invocations for each method.
        Returns:
        this.

      • inThatOrder

        void inThatOrder()

        Verifies that the mock methods were called (with matching arguments) in the order they were called within the lambda passed to assertMocks.

        This method is tolerant of other mock invocations in between the matched calls.

        Note that this does not directly verify that all methods were called (although it does have that side-effect). You may find it more readable (and will give better failure messages) to chain this with one of the wereAllCalled() family of methods.

        Throws AssertionFailedError if the methods were not called in the order given.

        Since:
        1.0

      • exclusivelyInThatOrder

        void exclusivelyInThatOrder()

        Verifies that the mock methods were called (with matching arguments) in the order they were called within the lambda passed to assertMocks.

        This method is not tolerant of other mock invocations in between the matched calls - it requires them to have been exclusively called, in the given order.

        Note that this does not directly verify that all methods were called (although it does have that side-effect). You may find it more readable (and will give better failure messages) to chain this with one of the wereAllCalled() family of methods.

        Throws AssertionFailedError if the methods were not called in the order given.
        Since:
        1.0

      • inAnyOrder

        void inAnyOrder()

        Verifies that the mock methods were called (with matching arguments) in any order. In the default implementation, this is a synonym for wereAllCalled().

        This method is tolerant of other mock invocations in between the matched calls.

        Throws AssertionFailedError if a single invocation wasn't matched, or MultipleFailuresError if multiple calls weren't matched. In the latter case, the individual calls that didn't match will each have a nested AssertionFailedError.

        Since:
        1.0
